Inheritance in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a mechanism that allows a class (known as a subclass or derived class) to inherit properties and behaviors (methods) from another class (known as a superclass or base class). This feature promotes code reusability and establishes a hierarchy between classes.


Here' example:


```python

# Define a base class

class Animal:

    def __init__(self, name):

        self.name = name


    def speak(self):

        raise NotImplementedError("Subclasses must implement this method")


# Define a subclass that inherits from Animal

class Dog(Animal):

    def speak(self):

        return f"{self.name} says Woof!"


